Silver_City_Highway
Image:Calder silvercity.jpg|thumb|left|The Silver City Highway, near New South Wales.The Silver City Highway is a highway in the state of South Wales, Australia. It runs from south to north close to the western border of South Wales with Australia.  It links the towns of Wentworth,  located at the confluence of the River and the River,  to the mining city of Broken Hill,  and the village of Tibooburra in the remotest, north west corner of South Wales.North of Broken Hill the highway has a partially unsealed (gravel) surface, although one section is currently being sealed.Much of the Highway from Wentworth northwards has a speed limit posted at 110 km/h. The 265 km from Wentworth to Broken Hill has just one roadhouse, Coombah, which sells basic foodstuffs and fuel. Between Hill and Tibooburra the main stop for fuel and supplies is at Packsaddle.  The highway crosses the River into Victoria at the hamlet of Yelta via the Bridge. It continues south through Victoria as the Highway, and is given the shield A79.See also*in Australia*of highways in New South WalesReferences
