Pietro_Belluschi
awards             Gold MedalMedal of ArtsPietro Belluschi (August 18, 1899  February 14, 1994) was an American architect, a leader of the Modern Movement in architecture, and was responsible for the design of over one thousand buildings.(Belluschi, Pietro. (2007). In Encyclopdia Britannica. Retrieved September 22, 2007, from: Encyclopdia Britannica Online) Born in Italy, Belluschis architectural career began as a draftsman in a Oregon firm.  He achieved a national reputation within about twenty years, largely for his 1947 aluminum-clad Equitable Building.  In 1951 he was named the dean of the School of Architecture and Planning, where he served until 1965, also working as collaborator and design consultant for many high-profile commissions, most famously the 1963 Pan Am Building.  He won the 1972 Gold Medal.Early lifePietro Belluschi was born in Italy in 1899.(Gragg, Randy. Belluschi revered as creative, spiritual architect. Oregonian, February 15, 1994.) He grew up in Italy and served in the Italian armed forces during War I when Italy was allied with Britain, France, and later the United States.( Serving in the army he fought against the Austrians at the battles of Caporetto and Vittorio Veneto.( After the war, Belluschi studied at the University of Rome, earning a degree in engineering in 1922.( He moved to the United States in 1923, despite speaking no English, and finished his educationas an exchange student on a scholarshipat University with a second degree in civil engineering.((() Instead of returning to Italy, he worked briefly as a mining engineer in Idaho earning $5 per day, but he then joined the architectural office of E. Doyle in Portland.( He remained in the U.S., as friends in Italy had cautioned him to not return home because of the rise to power of Mussolini and the Fascist government.(CareerImage:St Marys Cathedral - San Francisco.jpg|thumb|of Saint Mary of the Assumption in San FranciscoAt Doyles office, Belluschi rose rapidly, soon becoming chief designer. After Doyle died in 1928, the firm took him into partnership in 1933. By 1943, Belluschi had assumed control of the firm by buying out all the other partners and was practicing under his own name. In 1951, Belluschi became Dean of the architecture and planning school at the Institute of Technology, a position he held until 1965.( When he accepted the position of dean and moved to Massachusetts, he transferred his office in Portland to the architecture firm Owings and Merrill. The move reduced his annual income from $150,000 to a salary of $15,000, but was prompted by health concerns attributable to the long hours of managing his office while still designing buildings.(Belluschi emerged as a leader in the development of American architecture, with the design of several buildings reflecting the influence of the International Style and his awareness of the technological opportunities of new materials. Most important was the Equitable Building (194447) in Portland, Oregon: a concrete frame office block clad in aluminum, and considered the first office building with a completely sealed air-conditioned environment.  Belluschis churches and residences differed from his commercial works. Although of Modern design, they fit within the development of the Northwest regional Modern idiom as they frequently used regional materials (particularly wood) and were often integrated with their suburban or rural sites.Awards and honorsBelluschi was elected a Fellow of the Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1952.()  He was a Fellow in the Institute of Architects (AIA), and was awarded the Gold Medal, the highest award given by the institute, in 1972.( He was awarded the Medal of Arts by the National Endowment for the Arts in 1991 for his lifetime achievements.(National Medal of Arts: Medalists. National Endowment for the Arts, accessed September 22, 2007.) Belluschi was on the jury that selected the winning design for the Veterans Memorial in D.C.(Clausen, Meredith L., Pietro Belluschi: Modern American Architect, Press, Cambridge, Massachusetts and London 1994, ISBN 0262032201)Later lifethumb|The Portland Art Museum.After leaving MIT in 1965, he continued to work. Belluschi would design and consult on both buildings and issues surrounding planning.( Pietro married Marjorie, and they had two sons: Peter and Anthony.( Pietro Belluschi died in Portland on February 14, 1994.(Worksthumb|Commonwealth Building in Portland.Image:Rohm and Haas.jpg|thumb|and HaasBelluschis designs include:* Pacific Telephone and Telegraph Company Building, southern addition, Portland,( 1926* Building, Portland, 1926* Public Service Building, Portland, Oregon, 1927* Belluschi Building, Art Museum (NRHP), 1932* Library Building (now Smullin Hall) at University, Oregon,(Gregg, Robert D. 1970. Chronicles of Willamette, volume II: Those eventful years of the President Smith era. Salem, Or: Willamette University.) 1938* Thomas More Catholic Church, Portland, 1940* Peter Kerr House, Oregon,(http://www.greatbuildings.com/buildings/Peter_Kerr_House.html) 1941* Chapel, River View Cemetery, Portland, 1942* Sweeney, Straub and Dimm Printing Plant, Portland (NRHP), 1946* Emmanuel Lutheran Church, Washington, 1946* Burkes House, Portland, 1947* Oregonian Building, Portland,(() 1947* Baxter Hall and Collins Hall, University, Oregon,( 1947* Psychology Building, College, Portland, 19471948* Equitable Building, Portland (NRHP), 1948* First Presbyterian Church, Grove, Oregon (NRHP), 1948* Sacred Heart Church, Oswego, Oregon, 1949* Zion Lutheran Church, Portland (NRHP) (Image), 1950* Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco, Portland Branch,( 1950* Central Lutheran Church, Portland,(Central Lutheran Church: Building History) 1951* Philip Neri Catholic Church, Portland, 1952* YWCA building, Salem,(Salem Online History, The YWCA: Celebrating 90 Years in Salem) 1954* Marion County Courthouse, Salem, Oregon,(Marion County Circuit Court:The Marion County Courthouse: A Historical Perspective) 1954* First Lutheran Church, Boston, 19541957* Temple Adath Israel, with Charles Frederick Wise, Pennsylvania, 19561957* College Library, Vermont, 19571958* Central Lutheran Church, Oregon,(University of Oregon News release: UO Gallery Shows Drawings by Pietro Belluschi) 1959* Temple Brith Kodesh, Rochester, New York, 19591963* First Methodist Church, Minnesota, 19621969* The Tully Hall at the School within the Center, York City, 19631969* Pan Am Building, Belluschi and Gropius as design consultants to Emery Roth & Sons, New York City, 1963* and Haas Corporate Headquarters, with George M. Ewing Co., Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, 1964* Church of the Christian Union, Rockford, Illinois, 1964-1965(The Unitarian Universalist Church)* Hoffman Columbia Plaza, now Unitus Plaza, Portland, Oregon, 1966* Immanuel Lutheran Church, Oregon, 1966* California Street, as consultant to Wurster, Benardi and Emmons and Owings and Merrill, Francisco, California, 1969* Boston Place, with Emery Roth & Sons, Massachusetts, 1970* of Virginia School of Architecture, 1970* of Saint Mary of the Assumption, San Francisco (collaborating with Luigi Nervi and others), 1971* Art Institute, with Architects Collaborative, Massachusetts, 1973* Meyerhoff Symphony Hall, Maryland, 19781982* M. Davies Symphony Hall, with Owings and Merrill, San Francisco, 1980* Financial Center, Boston, 1983* Bancorp Tower, as consultant to Owings and Merrill, Portland, 1983* United Hebrew Congregation, Chesterfield, Missouri, 19861989* Hills Christian Church, Beaverton, Oregon (198789) (Clausen, Meredith L.  Spiritual Space: The Religious Architecture of Pietro Belluschi, University of Washington Press; First Edition, August 1992.)* Centennial Tower and Wheeler Sports Center, Fox University ( George Fox University: Centennial Clock Tower,)(George Fox University Athletic Facilities, Newberg, Ore.) 1991* Breitenbush Hall, State Hospital, Salem (NRHP)(Architects Associated with Oregon State Hospital)* Abbey School campus, Rhode Island* Uncle Tobys Story House, Blue Wing Lodge, Guardians Lodge, Kiwanis Lodge, Namanu, Oregon* Lacamas Summer Home, Camas, Washington* Chapel of Christ the Teacher, of Portland(University of Portland: Campus Ministry: Prayer Schedule)References External links * Oregon Blue Book biography* 1983 interview from the Smithsonians Archives of American ArtBelluschiBelluschiBelluschiBelluschiBelluschi
