Darryl_Sittler
 halloffame  1989Darryl Glen Sittler (born September 18, 1950) is a retired professional hockey player who played in the Hockey League from 1970 until 1985 for the Maple Leafs, the Flyers and the Red Wings. He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1989.On February 7, 1976, Sittler set an NHL record that still stands for most points scored in one game. He recorded ten points (six goals, four assists) against the Bruins.Playing careerToronto Maple LeafsSittler grew up in Jacobs, Ontario and played minor hockey in nearby Elmira. He was drafted out of the Junior B Sugar Kings by the Nationals, soon renamed the Knights, and played under coaches Broda and Guidolin. Sittler was selected eighth overall by the Maple Leafs in the NHL Amateur Draft. He was named team captain on September 10, 1975 after Keon left the team to play in the WHA following a contract dispute with Leafs owner Ballard.In his first season as captain, Sittler finished the season with 41 goals and 59 assists, being the first Leaf ever to reach the one hundred point mark. A few months later, he tied the playoff record for most goals in one game, with five against the Flyers. That summer, in the inaugural Canada Cup, he scored in overtime to win the final series for Team Canada over Czechoslovakia.On February 7, 1976 in a game between Toronto and Boston at Maple Leaf Gardens, Sittler set an NHL record that still stands by tallying 6 goals and adding 4 assists for 10 points. All his points were scored against rookie goalie Dave Reece in an 11-4 Maple Leaf victory.In 197778, Sittlers 117 points ranked him third in regular season scoring behind Lafleur and Trottier, and also earned him a Second Team All-Star selection. Sittlers scoring totals remained a Leafs record until being surpassed by Gilmour in 199293. During the 1978 playoffs, the Leafs upset the York Islanders in the quarter-finals, winning on an overtime goal by McDonald in Game 7 before being swept by the eventual Stanley Cup champion Canadiens in the Conference Finals.The 197879 season saw Sittler suffer some knee problems and miss 10 games. It was also the year that Leafs owner Ballard fired and then rehired coach Neilson, a process which saw Sittler lobby on the players behalf for Neilsons reinstatement.Sittlers relationship with Ballard slowly deteriorated, particularly after Ballard hired Imlach as general manager in July 1979. Imlach and Ballard both had strained relations with NHLPA executive director Eagleson who, as a player agent, represented more than a dozen Leafs, including Sittler and his best friend and linemate, Lanny McDonald. Imlach believed Sittler had too much influence on the team and tried to undermine his authority with the players. When Sittler and goaltender Palmateer agreed to appear on the TV show Showdown, as negotiated by the NHLPA, Imlach went to court to try to get injunction to stop them. When Imlach said that he was open to offers for Sittler from other teams, Eagleson said it would cost $500,000 to get Sittler to waive the no-trade clause in his contract. So, instead of trading Sittler, Imlach sent McDonald to the woeful Colorado Rockies on December 29, 1979. In response, Sittler ripped the captains C off his sweater, later commenting that a captain had to be the go-between with players and management, and he no longer had any communication with management.(Daryl Sittlers longest year, Frank Orr, Star, March 16, 1980, p. C3.) Ballard would liken Sittlers actions to burning the Canadian flag.(Maple Leaf forever? Sittler will stay put at least this season, Ken McKee, Star, March 8, 1980, p. C3.)Through the summer, Ballard insisted that Sittler would not be back with the Leafs. But before the start of the 198081 season, Sittler and Ballard appeared together at a news conference described as all smiles and buddy-buddy(Peace is wonderful, but ..., Frank Orr, Star, September 5, 1980, p. D1.) to announce that Sittler would be at training camp. He showed up with the C back on his sweater, reassuming the role of team captain. Sittler had arranged the talks with Ballard on his own.( The discussions took place with Imlach hospitalized following his second heart attack. At the news conference, Ballard said the real battle had been between Imlach and Eagleson, and Sittler just got caught in the crossfire.During the 198182 season, Ballard considered Imlachs health to be too poor for him to continue as general manager. But even with Imlach gone, Sittlers relationship with the Leafs worsened to the point where he told Ballard and acting general manager Gerry McNamara at the end of November that he would waive his no-trade clause if he was sent to the Flyers or the North Stars. In the first week of December, Eagleson agreed to terms with Flyers owner Snider and North Stars general manager Nanne.(Sittler saga finally ends, Wayne Parrish, Star, January 21, 1982, p. D1.) But it took another seven weeks for the Leafs to make a deal. During that time, Sittler added the Islanders and Sabres to the list of teams he could be traded to. On January 5, 1982, on advice from his physician, Sittler walked out on the Leafs, saying he was mentally depressed because a trade was taking so long to complete.Philadelphia FlyersFinally, on January 20, 1982, the 31 year-old Sittler was traded to the Flyers for Costello plus the Whalers second-round pick in the 1982 draft (used by the Leafs to select Ihnak), and future considerations, which ended up being Ken Strong. Only Ihnacak would play regularly for the Leafs. In 1980, Imlach had rejected an offer from Philadelphia, who were said to be willing to trade MacLeish and Dupont for Sittler.(Leafs seek youth in any exchange for Darryl Sittler, Ken McKee, Star, February 19 1980, p. F1.)With the Flyers in 198283, Sittler earned his fourth All-Star game appearance and he returned to the Flyers the following season. Before the 198485 season, Sittler was told that he would be named the Flyers team captain. On the day the announcement was to be madeSittler even had a brief speech prepared(Sittler considering retirement, Rick Fraser, Star, October 12, 1984, p. B1.)he was instead told by Flyers newly-appointed general manager Clarke that he had been traded to the Red Wings for Craven and Joe Paterson. It was this incident that Sittler described as the biggest disappointment of his life. Clarke cant come close to realizing how much he hurt me, and my family, that day, he wrote in his 1991 autobiography.(Sittler, Darryl Sittler & Chris Goyens, Macmillan Canada, 1991, p. 224.) Sittler contemplated retirement and did not report to the Wings for a few days, but then joined the team. He had an unproductive season, struggling to get ice time under coach Polano, and finishing the year with the worst goals-per-game average of his NHL career. The Red Wings bought out Sittlers contract after the end of the season. He received a one-year contract offer from the Canucks, but decided to retire.RetirementSittler was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1989. In 1991, a year after Ballard died, he rejoined the Leafs organization as a consultant under new general manager Fletcher. In 1998, he was ranked number 93 on The Hockey News list of the 100 Greatest Hockey Players and on February 8, 2003, Sittlers number 27 was honoured by the Leafs.(Banner night for Leafs; Sundin hot on Sittlers special evening, Paul Hunter, Star, February 9, 2003, p. E1.)Vancouver songwriters Dan Swinimer and Jeff Johnson wrote a country song commemorating Sittlers 60th birthday called The Darryl Sittler Song. Since retirement Sittler has also been serving as a director to a number of mineral exploration companies, including Royal Nickel and Wallbridge Mining.Terry FoxIn July 1980 Sittler presented Fox with his All-Star Team jersey in Phillips Square in front of a crowd of over 10,000 supporters. Fox had said that Sittler was one of his favourite athletes.Career statisticsSee also* of NHL statistical leaders* of NHL players with 1000 points* of players with 5 or more goals in an NHL gameReferencesExternal links**SittlerSittlerSittlerSittlerja:SittlerSittler
