George_L._Shoup
RepublicanGeorge Laird Shoup (June 15, 1836 December 21, 1904) was the first Governor of Idaho, serving a short time after statehood in 1890 before becoming one of the states first United States Senators.Laird Shoup (NSHC.After being devastated financially in the panic of 1857, Shoup moved to Territory in 1859 to engage in mining and merchandising near Peak. During the Civil War he enlisted with the independent scouts working in Mexico, Colorado, and Texas. He was commissioned colonel when the Colorado Cavalry was formed and took part in the of Apache Canyon during the Civil War and the Creek massacre during the War.(Page 148 and pages 162 and 163, Life of George Bent: Written From His Letters, by George E. Hyde, edited by Savoie Lottinville, University of Oklahoma Press (1968), hardcover, 390 pages; trade paperback, 280 pages (March 1983) ISBN 0806115777 ISBN 978-0806115771)After the war Shoup moved to Virginia City, Territory, and then settled in Salmon, Territory, a city that he helped found. Shoup was appointed commissioner to organize Lemhi County, and in 1874 he was elected to the territorial legislature. With few interruptions, he served on the National Committee for Idaho from 1880 to 1904.In April 1889, President Harrison appointed Shoup governor of Idaho Territory. Shoup remained in the position until July 1890, when Idaho became a state and Idaho Territory ceased to exist. Shoup was elected the states first governor in October.Shoup served as governor of the new state for only a few weeks. In November 1890 the Idaho Legislature elected him to the States Senate. Shoup resigned as governor in December to take his Senate seat. He was succeeded as governor by Lieutenant Governor B. Willey.In the Senate Shoup had many interests, including pensions, education, and military affairs. He was chairman of the Committee on Territories. In that position he advocated liberal and just treatment of the Native Americans. Shoup was reelected to a full six-year term in the Senate by the Idaho Legislature in 1894, but in 1900 he was defeated by  Democrat Dubois.In 1910, the state of Idaho donated a marble statue of Shoup to the Statuary Hall Collection.NotesExternal links**Laird ShoupL. Shoupja:Laird Shoup
