OHiggins_Region
 iso_code                 CL-LIThe VI OHiggins Region () is one of Chiles 15 first order divisions. It is subdivided into three provinces. It is named in honour of Bernardo OHiggins Riquelme, one of Chiles fathers.The OHiggins Region is bordered to the west by the Ocean, to the east by the of Argentina, to the north by the Valparaso and Santiago Metropolitan Regions, and to the south by the Region. It extends approximately between the parallels of 3351 and 3501 south latitude, and between the meridian of 7002 west longitude and the Pacific Ocean.The capital and largest city of the region is Rancagua. The second major town is San Fernando.GeographyIn pre-Quaternary times extensive Nothofagus forests covered much of OHiggins Region.(Thomas T. Veblen, Robert S. Hill and Jennifer Read (1996) The Ecology and Biogeography of Nothofagus Forests, Yale University Press, 403 pages  ISBN 0-300-06423-3)The OHiggins Region is part of the very restricted range of the endangered Wine Palm, chilensis; in prehistoric times this Chilean endemic tree had a significantly larger range.(C. Michael Hogan (2008) Chilean Wine Palm: Jubaea chilensis, GlobalTwitcher.com, ed. Nicklas Stromberg)HistoryFrom 9000 BCE to 300 BCE (the Archaic Period), the humans who inhabited the region moved between the coast and the valley as well as the Andes. At sites such as Pichilemu, Chuil and Bucalemu, they left trash deposits or shell middens bearing testimony to their raids . During the Period (300 BCE - 1470 CE), the inhabitants experienced changes in their way of life, the most important being the cultivation of vegetables and the manufacture of clay objects. From 600 CE onwards, they started cultivating beans, maize, squashes, pumpkins and Quinoa. All of these except Quinoa and some types of maize required irrigation, which prompted them to move to the banks of creeks and rivers. During this period, groups of people lived in Quincha houses with straw roofs, in the vicinity of irrigation channels and horticulture crops, a style of life attributable to the Promaucaes or Picunches and to the Chiquillanes. During the Colonial Period (1541 CE to 1811 CE), the region became dominated, like the rest of the country, by the Spanish, and a system of ranching became predominant .DemographyThe OHiggins region contains a large part of the rural population (surpassed only by the Region). Amongst the highly populated cities, Rancagua (206,971 inhabitants) stands out for having been transformed, in recent times, into an outskirt of Santiago. It is close being located 87 km south of Santiago. It is the capital of the Province as well the OHiggins Region. According to the census of 2002,(Chile: Proyecciones y Estimaciones de Poblacin. Total Pas 1950-2050 Instituto National de Estadsticas (INE)) other densely populated cities are: San Fernando (49,519 inhabitants); Rengo (30,891); Machal (23,920); Graneros (21,616); Vicente de Tagua Tagua (18,914); Santa Cruz (18,603); Chimbarongo (13,795); Francisco de Mostazal (12,037); and Pichilemu (9,027) a well-known beach resort city founded by Ross Edwards in the late 19th century.EconomyThe main industrial and export activity takes place at CODELCOs Teniente mine, which contributes 7.7% of Chiles copper production. The ore is processed at the Sewell and Coln concentrator plants, smelted and refined at Caletones, and shipped from the port of San Antonio, in the Valparaso Region. Byproducts include molybdenum and silver.Agriculture contributes 30.1% of the regions GDP. One out of every four hectares of fruit orchards in Chile is in the OHiggins Region. The main crops are apples and pears, followed by table grapes, plums, kiwis, and nectarines.Manufacturing activity in the region is mostly related to mining, agribusiness, and food and beverages. One particular growth area is the production of fruit juices and pulp, and dehydrated fruit.Over the past few years, there has been significant development in the forestry sector, especially plantations of eucalyptus and radiata pine.Law and GovernmentThe region is governed by an intendant, whois appointed by the president. Moises Saravia is the current intendant (2011).The administration of the region rests with the regional government, which is headed by the intendant and the regional council (Consejo Regional de Chile). The latter comprises sixteen regional administrators, who are elected indirectly (ten from Cachapoal, four from Colchagua, and two from Cardenal Caro).Administrative divisionsFor purposes of interior administration, the OHiggins region is divided into three provinces:* Province, capital: Rancagua,* Province, capital: San Fernando,* Caro Province, capital: Pichilemu.The provinces are subdivided into 33 communes.{| cellpadding4 cellspacing0 stylealign:center; margin: 0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%; width70% aligncenter|-!colspan2|Politico-administrative divisions of the OHiggins Region|-|width75%||width25% aligncenter||}CultureThis area is known as the huaso province after the name of the Chilean cowboy, the huaso. Sashes and mantas  traditional items of the huaso costume  are woven in Doihue on heavy vertical looms. Designs imitate vine leaves, bunches of grapes, pines and copihues. Other designs of colored stripes are woven on horizontal looms.The population is a mixture of both European (including Argentinan immigrants) and Indigenous races and cultures, thus the region has a homogeneous culture known as Chileanidad is present and a mestizo imprint is evident.The OHiggins region had Spanish (most notably are Andalusian, Basque, Aragonese and Navarrese) settlers and other European immigrants in its history. The French and Italian families established agriculture with the key wine industry from their vineyards. Breweries can be found as well to produce beer is the legacy of German and Swiss immigration. Livestock herding was co-founded by some British, Greek and Yugoslavian settlers.The Wine Route is one of the main tourist attractions of the valley and has resulted in an important economic revival.In the late 19th century, a small number of Cherokee and Oklahoman settlers of American Indian descent from Territory, USA came to the OHiggins region by the Chilean government. The Cherokee were displaced by white Anglo settlement in Oklahoma at the time, so they accept an offer to settle in Chile, then founded a cooperative farm (1880s) Ovasso an language word for the end or edge. The farm settlement was abandoned from lack of successful farm production.  There is quite a small colony of Aartis or Artas, East Indians descended from hired rail workers came from then India in the early 20th century. The Artas are from a Hindi language word for shining cloth that was wore over their bodies during Hindu religious rites, but they rather call themselves desis.  Due to a relatively close distance to Santiago, a more urban influence has been present in the local culture. The largest city, Rancagua is fast-becoming a suburb of Santiagos upper-class professional workforce. Regional FestivalsAnniversariesDateEnglish NameSpanish NameNotes12 OctoberDisaster of RancaguaDesastre de RancaguaIn memory of the Battleof Rancagua which occurred in 1814ReferencesExternal links*The Libertador Bernardo OHiggins Region at the Chilean government website * Regional government of the OHiggins Region *VI.cl: Portal de la Sexta Regin (Portal for the Sixth Region) *Pichilemus official website OHiggins()dOHigginsOHigginsda:OHiggins-regionendel Libertador General Bernardo OHigginsdel Libertador General Bernardo OHigginsGeneral Bernardo OHigginseskualdeadu Libertador General Bernardo OHigginsde OHigginsdi OHigginsdel Libertador General Bernardo OHiggins()Libertatoris Ducis Bernardi OHigginiiGenerolo Bernardo OHiginso regionasGeneral Bernardo OHigginsja:no:OHigginspl:Libertadorde OHigginsdel Libertador General Bernardo OHigginssuyu()of OHigginsde OHigginsblgesi Rehiyon 