Preov
File:Nabrezie Torysy Presov.jpg|thumb|right|Torysa riverbank in PreovPreov ( is a city in eastern Slovakia. It is the seat of the administrative Region (). With a population of approximately 100,000, it is the third-largest city in the country.Historically, the city has been known in German as Eperies (between 1938 and 1945 also Preschau),  Eperjes in Hungarian, Fragopolis in Latin, Preszw in Polish, Peryeshis in Romany,  (Pryashev)  in Russian and  (Priashiv) in Rusyn and Ukrainian.CharacteristicsThe city is a showcase of Baroque, Rococo and architecture. In the historical center, the main street is lined with churches and other buildings built in these styles.  In the suburbs, however, the Soviet influence is clearly evident through the massive concrete apartment buildings (the panelky) of the Sdlisk (housing estates) and the Sekov district. More Soviet-style architecture is seen in the government buildings near the city center.Significant industries in the city include mechanical and electrical engineering companies and the clothing industry. Solivary, the only salt mining and processing company in Slovakia, also operates in the city. The city is a seat of a Greek Catholic metropolitan see.Many concerts, operas, operettas and stage plays are performed at the new building of the Jon Zborsk Theatre (Divadlo Jona Zborskho), as well as at the older theatre premises.The city and the region were contenders for Capital of Culture 2013.(See Presov 2013 website)HistoryHabitation in the area around Preov dates as far back as the Paleolithic period. The oldest discovered tools and mammoth bones are 28,000 years old. Continuous settlement dates back to the 8th century.The first record of a school dates from 1429. In 1572, salt mining began in Solivar (at that time a nearby town, now part of Presov). Preovs increased importance meant that in 1647 it became the seat of the (ari) county.Vrani, a Croatian() prelate, writer, diplomat and of Esztergom, died in Preov in 1573.In 1667 the important Evangelic Lutheran College of Eperjes was established by Lutherans in the town. In 1687 twenty-four prominent citizens and noblemen were executed for supporting the uprising of Thkly.At the beginning of the 18th century, the population was decimated by the plague and fires and was reduced to a mere 2,000 inhabitants. By the second half of the century, however, the town had recovered; crafts and trade improved, and new factories were built. In 1752 the salt mine in Solivar was flooded. Since then salt has been extracted from salt brine through boiling.In 1870 the first railway was built. This was a line connecting the town to Koice. At the end of the 19th century, the town introduced electricity, telephone, telegraph and a sewage systems. In 1887 fire destroyed a large part of the town. In 1920, after the of Trianon, Eperjes became part of the newly created Czechoslovakia as Preov. During War II, the nearby town of Koice again became part of Hungary as a result of the Vienna Award. As a result, many institutions moved from Koice to Preov, thus increasing the towns importance. In 1944, a professional Slovak Theatre was established in Preov.After 1948, during the Communist era in Czechoslovakia, Preov became an industrial center. The population increased rapidly from 28,000 in 1950 to 52,000 in 1970 and 91,000 in 1990.GeographyPreov lies at an altitude of  above sea level and covers an area of .() It is located in the north-eastern Slovakia, at the northern reaches of the Basin, at the confluence of the Torysa River with its tributary Sekov.  Mountain ranges nearby include vrchy (south-east), vrchovina (south-west), Bachure (west) and ergov (north). The neighbouring city of Koice is  to the south. Preov is about  south of the Polish border,  north of the Hungarian border and is some  northeast of Bratislava (by road).ClimatePreov lies in the north temperate zone and has a climate with four distinct seasons. It is characterized by a significant variation between hot summers and cold, snowy winters.dateAugust 2010Demographicsdm.jpg|thumb|right|Concathedral in Preov Presov 0858.jpg|thumb|right|Neptunes fountain on the Hlavn ulica (Main Street) in PreovIn 1910 Preov had a population of 16,323, of which 7976 were Hungarians, 6494 Slovaks and 1404 Germans. In addition there were 170 Roma, 47 Rusyns, 4 Croatians, 2 Serbs and 226 others.Preov had a population of 91,621 in 2005. According to the 2001 census, 93.7% of the inhabitants were Slovaks, 1.4% Roma, 1.2% Rusyns, 1.1% Ukrainians, 0.8% Czechs, and 0.2% Hungarians. The religious make-up was 66.8% Catholics, 13.6% people with no religious affiliation, 8.9% Greek Catholics, 4.8% Lutherans and 1.68% Orthodox.(Before War II Preov also had a large Jewish population and housed a major Jewish museum. Plaques in the town hall and a memorial in the surviving synagogue record that 6,400 Jews were deported from the town under the Tiso government of the Slovak Republic to the camps run by the Nazi regime of Germany.EducationInstitutions of tertiary education in the city are the of Preov with 12,549 students, including 867 doctoral students,() and the private Business College ISM Slovakia in Preov, with 455 students.() In addition, the Faculty of Manufacturing Technologies of the University of Koice is based in the city.There are 15 public schools, six private primary schools and two religious primary schools.() Overall, they enroll 9,079 pupils.( The citys system of education consists of 10 gymnasia with 3,675 students,() 4 specialized schools with 5,251 students() and 11 schools with 5,028 students.()()Hiking trails* walking route E8** Preov - Mihov - Kurimka - Dukla - Iwonicz-Zdrj  Rymanw-Zdrj - Puawy  Tokarnia (778 m)  Kamie (717 m)  Komacza - Cisna - Grne - Tarnica - Woosate.See also* of people from Preov* ari Brewery* Court of PreovInternational relationsTwin towns  Sister citiesPreov is twinned with:References* Official History of Preov* Preov town hall (July 2002), Preov - city profile.  Retrieved in June 2004 from http://www.pis.sk/jpis/obsah/html/presov_profile.htm.Bibliography*NotesExternal links* Webpage of the town* DPMP - Public Transport Official Site* Preov information from Slovakia.org* Video about Preovar:be-x-old:bg:cs:Preovda:Preovde:Preovet:Preovel:es:Preoveo:Preovfr:Preovhr:Preovid:Preovit:Preovhe:ka:la:Epurieslv:Preovalt:Preovasli:Preov(Szlovkia)mk:nl:Preovja:frr:Preovno:Preovnn:Preovpnb:pl:Preszwpt:Preovro:Preovrue:ru:simple:Preovsk:Preovsr:fi:Preovsv:Preovuk:vi:Preovvo:Preovwar:Preovzh:
