Christ_the_Redeemer_(statue)
 governing_body Christ the Redeemer () is a statue of Jesus Christ in de Janeiro, Brazil; considered the largest Deco statue in the world and the worlds 5th largest statue. It is  tall, including its  pedestal, and  wide. It weighs 635 tonnes (625 long,700 tons), and is located at the peak of the  Corcovado mountain in the Forest National Park overlooking the city. A symbol of Christianity, the statue has become an icon of Rio and Brazil.()  It is made of reinforced concrete and soapstone, and was constructed between 1922 and 1931.()()()Historyleft|thumb|A view of the statue, as seen from a helicopter.The idea for erecting a large statue atop Corcovado was first suggested in the mid-1850s, when Catholic priest Pedro Maria Boss requested financing from Princess Isabel to build a large religious monument. Princess Isabel did not think much of the idea and it was dismissed in 1889, when Brazil became a republic with laws mandating the of church and state.() The second proposal for a landmark statue on the mountain was made in 1921 by the Catholic Circle of Rio.( The group organised an event called Semana do Monumento (Monument Week) to attract donations and collect signatures to support the building of the statue. The donations came mostly from Brazilian Catholics.( The designs considered for the Statue of the Christ included a representation of the cross, a statue of Jesus with a globe in his hands, and a pedestal symbolizing the world.() The statue of Christ the Redeemer with open arms, a symbol of peace, was chosen.thumb|right|250px|A view of the statue from the base.Local engineer da Silva Costa designed the statue; it was sculpted by French sculptor Landowski.() A group of engineers and technicians studied Landowskis submissions and the decision was made to build the structure out of concrete (designed by Caquot) instead of steel, more suitable for the cross-shaped statue.( The outer layers are soapstone, chosen for its enduring qualities and ease of use.(  Construction took nine years, from 1922 to 1931 and cost the equivalent of . The monument was opened on October 12, 1931.(( The statue was meant to be lit by a battery of floodlights triggered remotely by shortwave radio pioneer Marconi, stationed  away in Rome,() but poor weather affected the signal and it had to be lit by workers in Rio.(In October 2006, on the statues 75th anniversary, Archbishop of Rio Cardinal Oscar Scheid consecrated a chapel (named after the patron saint of BrazilSenhora Aparecida, or Our Lady of the Apparition,) under the statue. This allows Catholics to hold baptisms and weddings there.(thumb|250px|left|A close up view of the face.The statue was struck by lightning during a violent electrical storm on Sunday, February 10, 2008 and suffered some damage on the fingers, head and eyebrows. A restoration effort was put in place by the Rio de Janeiro state government and archdiocese to replace some of the outer soapstone layers and repair the lightning rods installed on the statue.()()()On April 15, 2010 graffiti was sprayed on the statues head and right arm. Mayor Paes called the act a crime against the nation and vowed to jail the vandals, even offering a reward of R$ 10,000 for any information that might lead to an arrest.()() The Military Police eventually identified house painter Paulo Souza dos Santos as the suspect of the act of vandalism. A World Wonder On July 7, 2007, in Lisbon (da Luz), Christ the Redeemer was named one of the Seven Wonders of the World in a list compiled by the Swiss-based The New Open World Corporation.() Leading corporate sponsors, including Bradesco and Globo, had lobbied to have the statue voted into the top seven.()RestorationDeclared a protected monument by the National Heritage Institute, IPHAN, in 2009, the Christ the Redeemer monument underwent restoration work in 1980 before the visit of Germano Wallerstein.In 1990, further restoration work was conducted through an agreement between the Archdiocese of Rio de Janeiro, media company Rede Globo, oil company Shell do Brasil, environment regulator IBAMA, National Heritage Secretariat SPHAN and the city government of de Janeiro.More work on the statue and its environs was conducted in 2003 and early 2010. In 2003, a set of escalators, walkways and elevators was installed to facilitate access to the platform surrounding the statue.The four-month restoration in 2010,( carried out by mining company Vale in partnership with the Archdiocese, focused on the statue itself. The statues internal structure was renovated and its soapstone mosaic covering was restored by removing a crust of fungi and other microorganisms and repairing small cracks. The lightning rods located in the statues head and arms were also repaired. New lighting fixtures would be installed at the root of the statue to produce an all new dynamic lighting effect on the statue.(Christ the Redeemer, YouTube video, accessed January 20, 2011.)The restoration involved one hundred people and used in excess of 60,000 pieces of stone, taken from the same quarry as the original statue.()  During the unveiling of the restored statue, it was illuminated with green and yellow lighting in support of the national football team playing in the FIFA World Cup.(Maintenance work needs to be conducted periodically due to the strong winds and rain to which the statue is exposed.()Portrayal in MediaFile:Christ on Corcovado mountain.JPG|thumb|600px|center|A panoramic view of Christ the Redeemer at the top of Corcovado mountain. In the background is Sugarloaf Mountain (centre) and Bay.Christ the Redeemer is featured in various works of fiction and media. The statue was featured in a major destruction scene in the movie 2012, when its arms collapse, and the rest of the statue fails at the knees and crumbles as it collides with the side of the mountain. This scene was highly controversial, especially when it was featured in a billboard campaign in Los Angeles, when Brazilian Multimedia Designer Sara Vieira spoke out against it. It is featured in the videogames Clancys H.A.W.X, 2,  3, Terranigma, of Duty: Modern Warfare 2, 117: Lost in Rio, IV: Beyond the Sword, Revolution, V and Birds Rio. It briefly appears in the bonus level of Hawks Pro Skater 3 on PlayStation. It can be seen in the video for Jacksons, Runaway and in the video for the Latin group & Yandels Pam video. The statue is also found in an episode of the the Third anime series. It is also seen in the Twilight series, as Edward is on the phone with Jacob in a pivotal scene of New Moon.  The statue watches over fictional Verona Beach in Luhrmanns + Juliet.  It is also shown on the  MTV show La Bam in which Margera battled Vito to win a $1000. It is also in Mr. Magoo. A parody of the statue is also seen in of Warcraft on an island called Janerios Point, the statue was damaged in the Cataclysm revealing a heart filled with riches. It has also been featured in the 2011 animated film Rio and fifth film Five (film) which had a major part based in de Janeiro. In the science fiction anime of the Galactic Heroes the planet Heinessen, capitol of the Free Planets Alliance, has a giant monument to its founder Arle Heinessen in which Heinessen is posed in the same position as Jesus in the Redeemer statue.  The statue is seen in the movie Twilight Saga: New Moon, in the background, when Edward calls Bellas home and Jacob answers the phone. The statue is also briefly shown in the trailer for Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn as the location of Edward & Bellas honeymoon.See alsoFile:Height comparison of notable statues 01.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Approximate heights of various notable statues:1. Temple Buddha 153 m2. of Liberty 93 m 3. Motherland Calls 91 m4. Lord Murugans Statue in Batu Caves 42.7 m5. Christ the Redeemer 39.6 m 6. Statue of David 5.17 m (sculpture 5.17 m + plinth  approximately 7.7 m)*al Divino Salvador del Mundo, Monument to the Savior of the World Salvador City, El Salvador*Redentore, Christ the Redeemer of Maratea, Italy*of Vung Tau in Vietnam (32 m)*Blessing in Manado, North Sulawesi, Indonesia (30m)*Cristo-Rei in Portugal: a 28 metre high monument of Christ the Redeemer*Rei of Dili: a 27 metre high statue in Dili, Timor-Leste*del Cubilete in Guanajuato, Mexico: a 23 meter high statue inspired by Christ the Redeemer*Cristo Rey in Jalisco: Inspired By Rio de Janeiros one*of the Ozarks in Arkansas, United States: a 20 meter high statue inspired by Christ the Redeemer*of Havana in Havana, Cuba: a 20 metre high statue inspired by Christ the Redeemer*the Redeemer of the Andes (Argentina/Chile)*de la Concordia in Cochabamba, Bolivia*de las Noas in Torren, Mexico*of the Abyss in various underwater locations*Christ the King (),  tall and weighing 440 tonnes.() in wiebodzin, Poland*del Pacfico, Lima, Peru, a 37 metre high statue erected in 2011.*of statues by height References  External links * Official web site* Useful information about Christ the Redeemer Statue (wiki format)* Map * BBC News Video about Poland and the Redeemer Statue* Government bulletin about the statues restoration * Free interactive 3D model of Statue of Christ the Redeemer Msihin heykli  () , -- ()  Redemptor de Rio de JaneiroKrista Spasitele (Rio de Janeiro)RedentorRedentor Kristuse kuju  Redentorde Kristo Savinto (Rio de Janeiro)Berreroslea (Rio de Janeiro)du Christ Rdempteuran Slnaitheoirdo Cristo Redentor   ()Krista IskupiteljaRedemptoroKristus PenebusRedentore  --saRedemptorPesttjs (statuja)RedentorAtpirkjo statulaMegvlt Krisztus szobra    de Verlosserja:(Rio de Janeiro)Chrystusa Zbawiciela w Rio de JaneiroRedentorMntuitorulQispichiq wanka- ()Spasite (Rio de Janeiro) (  )de Janeiron Kristus-patsasRedentor ()  ( )th:sa heykeli()Cha Kit Cu Th (Rio de Janeiro)nga Manurubos (estatuwa)zh:
